From: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Date: 2026-05-13
Subject: [PATCH] ps4_mts: v112 — re-arm BAR+0x204 after bit-18 handshake

v111 fired the bit-18 handshake correctly (boot log confirmed:
"v111: bit-18 handshake fired — exited init mode") and the bit-18
storm went from ~5,000 IRQs/sec to zero (total_irq stayed at 1 for
30+ seconds).  But TX/RX stayed dead with `BAR+0x50 = 0x40` (RX_AVAIL
asserted by MAC) and `BAR+0x204 = 0`.

Re-reading the Orbis mts_intr decompile @ 0xffffffffc85edcf0 more
carefully: the function has a FIRST-CALL SETUP at the TOP of every
ISR entry:

  if (softc+0x309c == 0) {     // first-call flag — set by previous
                                // bit-18 handshake to 0
    softc+0x309c = 1;
    BAR+0x204 = 0x10001388;    // RE-ARM master IRQ block
    BAR+0x54 = 0x7bfffe;
  }

So Orbis's BAR+0x204 PING-PONGS: re-armed at every ISR entry,
briefly cleared during the bit-18 handshake, re-armed again on the
next entry.  v111 did the clear but never the re-arm → no further
MSIs delivered → ISR never re-entered → TX/RX dead.

This patch adds the re-arm INLINE after the clear (since our ISR
doesn't have Orbis's per-call first-call setup).  Two new writes:
  - udelay(10)  to let the MAC's state machine fully transition
  - writel(MTS_IRQ_ENABLE_FULL_VAL, BAR+0x204)  re-arm

EXPECTED on success: after v112 bit-18 handshake fires, total_irq
keeps growing (was 1 in v111).  RX_AVAIL bit 6 fires as a proper
IRQ.  NAPI poll runs.  RX packets count up.  If link bit 0 latches
in BAR+0x04 → TX starts flowing too.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
---
 drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c | 16 +++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 15 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
@@ -967,9 +967,23 @@
 		writel(0, mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_ENABLE_FULL);
 		writel(mts->saved_irq_mask, mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_MASK);
 		(void)readl(mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_MASK);
+		/*
+		 * v112: Orbis's mts_intr re-arms BAR+0x204 = 0x10001388 at the
+		 * TOP of every ISR call (gated on softc+0x309c==0).  We don't
+		 * have a per-call first-call setup, so we re-arm inline here
+		 * after clearing.  Without this, no further MSIs are delivered:
+		 * v111 cleared BAR+0x204 = 0 and stayed there → total_irq stuck
+		 * at 1, MAC asserted RX_AVAIL in BAR+0x50 but ISR never re-entered.
+		 * The udelay(10) gives the MAC's state machine a chance to fully
+		 * transition out of init mode before we re-arm.
+		 */
+		udelay(10);
+		writel(MTS_IRQ_ENABLE_FULL_VAL, mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_ENABLE_FULL);
+		(void)readl(mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_ENABLE_FULL);
 		dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
-			 "v111: bit-18 handshake fired — exited init mode (BAR+0x204=0, BAR+0x54=0x%08x)\n",
-			 mts->saved_irq_mask);
+			 "v112: bit-18 handshake completed — re-armed BAR+0x204=0x%08x BAR+0x54=0x%08x\n",
+			 readl(mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_ENABLE_FULL),
+			 readl(mts->bar + MTS_IRQ_MASK));
 		return IRQ_HANDLED;
 	}
